# Flow generation recipes

These three scripts use the same `bundle_add_flow` engine that powers
`databricks labs sdp-meta bundle-add-flow`, but call it programmatically so
you can scale to hundreds of tables without typing each one.

All recipes default to **dry-run** — they print what they would write but do
not modify `conf/onboarding.{{if eq .onboarding_file_format "yaml"}}yml{{else}}json{{end}}`. Add `--apply` once the
preview looks right.

| Recipe | When to use it | Discovery source |
|---|---|---|
| `from_uc.py` | Source tables already exist in UC and you want one delta-source flow per table | `WorkspaceClient.tables.list(catalog, schema)` |
| `from_volume.py` | Source files land as one subdirectory per table under a UC volume (or local path during testing) | `WorkspaceClient.files.list_directory_contents(volume_path)` |
| `from_topics.py` | You have N Kafka or Event Hubs topics to onboard against the same broker / namespace | `--topics a,b,c` or `--topics-file conf/samples/topics.txt` |
| `from_inventory.py` | You have a hand-curated list (Excel, JSON, JIRA ticket) of `system -> [tables]` and want naming conventions applied programmatically | A literal `INVENTORY` dict you edit in the file |

## Quick start

```bash
# 1) Mirror every Delta table from raw.landing as a delta-source flow
python recipes/from_uc.py --source-catalog {{.uc_catalog_name}} --source-schema landing
python recipes/from_uc.py --source-catalog {{.uc_catalog_name}} --source-schema landing --apply

# 2) Treat each subdirectory under a UC volume as a cloudFiles source
python recipes/from_volume.py --volume-path /Volumes/{{.uc_catalog_name}}/landing/files
python recipes/from_volume.py --volume-path /Volumes/{{.uc_catalog_name}}/landing/files --apply

# 3) 10 Kafka topics off the same broker
python recipes/from_topics.py \
    --source-format kafka \
    --bootstrap-servers "broker1:9092,broker2:9092" \
    --topics-file conf/samples/topics.txt \
    --apply

# 4) 10 Event Hubs in the same namespace
python recipes/from_topics.py \
    --source-format eventhub \
    --bootstrap-servers "my-eh-namespace.servicebus.windows.net:9093" \
    --topics orders,customers,events,payments,shipments \
    --apply

# 5) Edit INVENTORY in from_inventory.py, then run
python recipes/from_inventory.py
python recipes/from_inventory.py --apply
```

## Pattern cheatsheet (when none of the recipes fits exactly)

Every shape below is a 4-line edit to `from_inventory.py` — the engine
handles auto-id, dedup, layer-aware key emission, and YAML/JSON.

**N cloudFiles paths that don't share a parent directory:**
```python
PATHS = [
    "/Volumes/raw/zone_a/orders/",
    "/Volumes/raw/zone_b/customers/",
    "s3://other-bucket/landing/events/",
]
flows = [
    FlowSpec(source_format="cloudFiles", source_path=p,
             bronze_table=p.rstrip('/').split('/')[-1],
             silver_table=p.rstrip('/').split('/')[-1])
    for p in PATHS
]
```

**N fully-qualified upstream Delta tables:**
```python
TABLES = ["raw.landing.orders", "raw.landing.customers", "ops.audit.events"]
flows = [
    FlowSpec(source_format="delta",
             source_database=fqn.rsplit('.', 1)[0],
             source_table=fqn.rsplit('.', 1)[1],
             bronze_table=fqn.rsplit('.', 1)[1],
             silver_table=fqn.rsplit('.', 1)[1])
    for fqn in TABLES
]
```

**Mixed source formats in one bundle** — call `bundle_add_flow` once per
list, or concatenate the lists; the engine writes them all atomically.

## What each recipe does on your behalf

* **Reads bundle defaults** from `resources/variables.yml`
  (target catalog, bronze/silver schemas, layer, dataflow group, file format).
  You don't pass them on the command line.
* **Auto-assigns `data_flow_id`** by continuing from the highest existing
  numeric id in the onboarding file (starts at 100 for an empty file).
* **Rejects duplicates** — if a generated id collides with one already in the
  file, the engine errors out without writing anything.
* **Respects the onboarding format** (YAML or JSON) — whatever the bundle was
  scaffolded with is what gets appended to.
* **Layer-aware** — bronze-only bundles only emit bronze keys, silver-only
  bundles only emit silver keys, combined bundles emit both.

## Building your own recipe

The primitive is `FlowSpec` — a dataclass with one optional field per
column. Anything you can express as a Python iterable of `FlowSpec` can be
passed straight to `bundle_add_flow`:

```python
from databricks.labs.sdp_meta.bundle import (
    BundleAddFlowCommand, FlowSpec, bundle_add_flow,
)

flows = [
    FlowSpec(
        source_format="cloudFiles",
        source_path=f"/Volumes/{{.uc_catalog_name}}/landing/files/{name}/",
        bronze_table=name,
        silver_table=name,
    )
    for name in my_table_names  # 1, 10, 1000 — same code path
]

bundle_add_flow(BundleAddFlowCommand(
    bundle_dir=".",
    flows=flows,
    dry_run=True,  # flip to False when you're happy
))
```

Use `from_inventory.py` as the closest starting point — it shows the basic
loop, the naming-convention helper, and the dry-run / apply pattern.
